description: pork rib soup made with a variety of Chinese herbs and spices.
flat rice noodles stir-fried with beef, served dry or with soup.
glutinous rice dumplings, usually filled with pork, mushrooms and stewed egg, steamed in bamboo leaves. Although it is Chinese in origin, it is also a favourite in Peranakan cuisine.
egg noodles with minced pork, braised mushroom, pork meatball and other ingredients, served dry or in soup. Usually the flat, tape-like mee pok noodle is used.

hand-made flat noodles served with vegetables, minced meat, sliced mushrooms, and an egg in an anchovy-based soup. Noodle variations are common. Ban mian refers to flat, long noodles; mee hoon kuay refers to flat, rectangular noodles; you mian refers to thin noodles.

also known as char kway or carrot cake, is a dish of steamed radish/daikon cakes diced and stir-fried with garlic, egg, chopped preserved radish, and sometimes with shrimp. This dish comes in black (fried with sweet dark soy sauce) or white (fried into an omelette) versions, with a chilli paste sometimes added.
thick, flat rice noodles stir-fried in dark soy sauce with shrimp, eggs, beansprouts, fish cake, cockles, green leafy vegetables, Chinese sausage and fried cubes of lard.
also romanised cha-su, cha siu, cha sio, caa siu and char siew, is barbecued pork in Cantonese cuisine.
an egg noodle dish with diced chicken meat.
a type of steamed rice cake served with preserved radish.
a rice vermicelli dish served with whole mud crab. It may be served dry or in soup and sometimes in a claypot.
prawns cooked with rice wine.

braised duck served with rice cooked with yam and shrimp. It can be served simply with white rice and a thick dark sauce, or with braised hard-boiled eggs, preserved salted vegetables, and hard bean curd (tau kua) on the side. Teochew boneless duck rice is a similar, but a more refined dish. The duck is deboned and sliced thinly, allowing the sauces to seep into the meat. Roasted duck rice is also commonly sold.
similar to bak chor mee, except that fish balls are used instead of minced pork.
a Singaporean soup-based served hot with bee hoon.
is served with frog legs, scallion, ginger and thick black sauce in a claypot with porridge in another claypot.

stir-fried prawn noodles cooked in a broth made from prawn heads and pork bones, topped with ingredients such as prawns, sliced pork belly, squid, egg, lard, and served with sambal chilli and lime at the side.
based on the Hainanese dish Wenchang chicken. It is considered Singapore's national dish.
is a dish consisting of steamed white rice smothered in a mess of curries and braised gravy.
shrimp paste chicken - chicken wings fried in a batter with fermented shrimp paste.
egg noodles and rice noodles stir-fried with egg, slices of pork, prawns and squid, and served and garnished with spring onion, lard, sambal chilli and lime (for adding lime juice to the dish).
a deep-fried bun-like pastry sometimes filled with bean paste.

a traditional breakfast dish. Kaya is a sweet coconut and egg jam which is spread over toasted bread. Combined with a cup of local coffee and a half-boiled egg, this constitutes a typical Singaporean breakfast.

a Teochew dish of flat, broad rice sheets in a soup made with dark soy sauce, served with pig offal, braised duck meat, various kinds of beancurd, preserved salted vegetables, and braised hard-boiled eggs.
a noodle dish characterised by its flat and yellow appearance, varying in thickness and width.

a thick, chewy pancake with a ground peanut and sugar filling. Other variations include grated coconut and red bean paste. This traditional snack also is served in blueberry, cheese and chocolate varieties.
a dish of omelette cooked with fresh raw oysters,tapioca starch and eggs.
a soup dish comprising pig brain with Chinese herbs.
a dish comprising stir-fried pig Fallopian tubes with vegetables and sambal chilli.
a soup-based variant of kuay chap
usually braised in black sauce and vinegar.
Hokkien/Teochew-style spring roll or rolled crÃªpe, stuffed with stewed turnip, Chinese sausage, shrimp and lettuce.
a noodles dish topped with shredded chicken, fish dumpling and mushroom.
a soup dish consisting of fish and vegetables.
a white vegetable dumpling with black soy sauce.
a rice porridge dish consumed with a selection of local side dishes.
a soup or stew made from turtle flesh.
thin braised rice vermicelli to which a choice of various gluten, vegetable, or beancurd-based delicacies may be added.
a dish that contains a varied selection of food items, including tofu filled with ground meat mixture or fish paste, fish balls, crab sticks, an assortment of vegetables and meat.
also called yew char kueh, fried dough crullers similar to those served in other Chinese cuisines around the world.
pickled vegetables or fruits with dried chilli, peanuts, and spices. Indian and Peranakan versions can also be found.
seafood and vegetables cooked in a sauce consisting of tamarind, coconut milk, chilli, and spices.
fried chicken dish consisting of fried chicken that is smashed with the pestle against mortar to make it softer and a relatively new culinary phenomenon of Indonesian origin.
also Ba'so, meatballs served with noodles.
mashed potato mixture that is fried into patties and eaten together with mee soto.
also known as epok-epok, a flaky pastry usually stuffed with curry chicken, potato cubes, and a slice of hard-boiled egg. Sardines are sometimes used in place of chicken.
a dish of dried beef lung cooked in spices.
bananas rolled in flour, fried, and eaten as a snack.
white jackfruit curry.
sweet potato leaves stewed in coconut milk.
deep fried crackers usually flavoured with shrimp, but sometimes with fish or vegetables.
rice cakes steamed in a square-shaped coconut leaf wrapping and usually served with satay.
shellfish cooked in a thick coconut milk-based gravy.
compressed rice cakes (see ketupat) in a spicy vegetable soup.
a rice snack with Indonesian origins.
steamed rice stir-fried in a wok, often mixed with other ingredients, such as eggs, vegetables and meat.
a steamed white rice served with an array â sometimes as many as 12, or more â of pre-cooked dishes, the mini banquet usually laid out style in small plates.
spicy fish cake grilled in a banana leaf wrapping.
fried catfish served with chilli paste.
beef soup.
a variant of Singaporean style rojak.
an omelette sandwich.
not a dish in itself, but a common chilli-based accompaniment to most foods.
grilled meat on skewers served with satay sauce (a spicy peanut sauce) and usually eaten with ketupat, cucumber and onions.
a mix of vegetables in coconut milk.
a soup dish mainly composed of meat and vegetables.
a spicy chicken soup that features chicken shreds, rice cakes and sometimes begedil.
a cone-shaped rice dish of Javanese origin. It is served with side dishes of vegetables and meat.
a fermented rice pancake.
rice and lentil pancake. Commonly served as a masala" version that includes spiced potatoes and is served with different types of sambar.
an Indian-Muslim dish originating from the Middle East. It consists of folded dough stuffed with spiced minced meat, onions and egg, and is often served with curry.
an Indian oven-baked flatbread.
rice flour noodle served with sugar and coconut usually eaten for breakfast.

a local evolution of the Pakistani and Indian paratha. It is a popular dish for breakfast and supper. It is a fried bread pancake that is crispy on the outside and soft on the inside. The dough is flipped to attain the right texture, then cooked quickly on a greased stove and served with curry or sugar. A plethora of modern variations are available, including egg, cheese, chocolate, masala, durian and even ice cream.
a local Tamil-Muslim dish of spiced mutton soup.
a local Tamil-Muslim dish of mutton or beef leg bones stewed in a spice. The bones are broken to allow the marrow to be eaten.
a dish consisting of mutton or beef bones stewed in a sweet and spicy red soup of mutton stock, tomatoes, ginger, chillies and spices.  It's considered a Singapore invention
chicken marinated in a mixture of spices and yogurt and cooked in a clay oven.
spicy, deep-fried snacks that are made from dhal, lentils or potato.
a Peranakan dish of chicken stewed with spices and Southeast Asian black nuts (buah keluak).

dish: Biryani (Indian variant) or Nasi Briyani (Malay variant)
description: a popular mixed rice dish commonly found in places offering Malay or Indian food.

dish: Cereal prawns (éº¦çè¾; mÃ i piÃ n xiÄ)
description: stir-fried prawns with sweetened cereal.
pasta served with chili crab.

a Peranakan dish of vermicelli noodles and fried bean curd served in a creamy coconut sauce with slices of shrimp, fish, and cockles. Can be served in a tamarind-filled variant with shredded mackerel and mangosteen.

a dish created by Singapore's Malayalee (an Indian ethnic group from Kerala) community with some Chinese and Malay influences. The head of a red snapper (ikan merah, literally red fish") stewed in curry consisting of varying amounts of coconut milk and tamarind juice
a Eurasian Singaporean curry dish with Portuguese and Peranakan influences. Includes chicken, cabbage, sausage, and bacon pieces stewed in a curry sauce.
a Peranakan chicken curry with a coconut milk base
a Singaporean thick rice noodles (bee hoon) in a coconut curry gravy with prawn and egg. Sometimes chicken, tau pok (beancurd puffs) or fish cake may be added.
steamed rice flour pastries with a sweet shredded coconut or peanut filling
a thin and crispy pastry tart shell filled with a spicy, sweet mixture of thinly sliced vegetables and prawns.
stir-fried flat rice noodles.
egg noodles with a spicy slightly sweet curry-like gravy. The gravy is made from sweet potatoes, curry powder, water, salted soybeans, dried shrimp and peanuts.
a dish of thin rice vermicelli.
yellow egg noodles stir fried with ghee, tomato sauce, chilli, eggs, vegetables, and various meats and seafood.
a spicy noodle soup dish.
a traditional fruit and vegetable salad dish of Indian origin and with Malay/Indonesian influences.
a dish of water spinach (kangkong) fried in sambal.
rice noodles served with cuttlefish, fried bean curd puffs, cockles and water spinach in satay sauce.
fried bean curd with sweet sauce.
hard shell crabs cooked in a black pepper sauce. Salted Egg crab and buttermilk crab are also common.
hard shell crabs cooked in chilli sauce, usually served with man tou, or deep fried buns.
an oyster omelette mixed with flour and fried, served garnished with coriander.
soft shell clams fried with sambal sauce
smothered in sambal and served on banana leaf, also known as ikan bakar in Malay.
a dish of pearled sago, sweet potatoes, yams, bananas, black-eyed peas, pandan leaves, sugar, and salt cooked in coconut milk and served hot or cold.
basic version consist of pandan jelly strips with coconut milk and gula melaka syrup with shaved iced; other ingredients which could be added are red beans, sweet corns, ice cream and even durians.
a light, refreshing soup with longan, barley, agar strips, lotus seeds and a sweet syrup, served either hot or cold. It is analogous to the Cantonese Ching bo leung.
a mound of grated ice on a base consisting of jelly, red beans, corn and attap seeds, topped with various kinds of coloured sugar syrups, palm sugar, rose syrup and evaporated milk.
small cakes or coconut milk based desserts that come in a variety of flavours, usually containing fruit such as durian or banana. Pandan is a common flavouring.
a rich, multi-layered cake-style kueh using a large amount of egg whites and studded with prunes.
a popular kueh with layers of alternating colour and a sweet, coconut taste.
a Teochew dish consisting of taro (locally known as yam) paste, coconut paste and ginkgo nuts.
a creamy dessert made of black glutinous rice and served with coconut cream.
mung beans in jelly, served hot with dough crullers.
